    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-09-28T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-09-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="396"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d396">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/9–2853: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lodge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-09-28T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >September 28, 1953—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 39. Re United Nations staff assessments,
                        <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 115.<note n="1" xml:id="d396fn1"
                        >Not printed.</note> I have asked Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_WADSWORTHJJ1">Wadsworth</persName> to handle this question for
                    me. It is his <pb facs="0646" n="618" xml:id="pg_618"/> view that on
                    administrative and legal grounds it would be preferable to adopt tax exemption
                    legislation. Such legislation would be difficult to obtain at present, in
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WADSWORTHJJ1">Wadsworth</persName>’s view.
                    Accordingly, he recommends Department request tax credit legislation for United
                    States nationals in international organizations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lodge</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
